metadata.name: What on Earth? #26
metadata.description:
'What on Earth?' expands upon the history of my last piece 'Terra'. This is a speculative scifi projection taking inspiration from the IPCC reports on climate change. This piece is an imagination of the possibility of the multiverse. 

It is a generative art piece that uses six base maps for the different types of earth. The two other layers are procedurally generated and overlayed on each other resulting in 6x4x5 possible combinations. However there is always a chance of getting multiple planetary accessories which increase the number of unique possible variations. Each of the pieces also come with their unique version of narrative embedded in the piece itself. 

Instruction:
Hover in the top right corner of the canvas to reveal a button to access the story and the settings. This is an interactive piece - click and drag to turn/play with your earth. 

Photosensitivity Warning: Viewer discretion is advised before you turn on 'Acid' inside settings. It involves flashing imagery and glitching effects.

metadata.name: MAGNETIK #79
metadata.description:
The output of MAGNETIK reminds me of what tornadoes do to our cities and buildings, yet I imagine the pieces that are about to break off and fly away to be made of metal foil and they do so because of a magnetic force that is pulling them away from where they belong‚Ä¶‚Ä®‚Ä®This one is also a charity run : ‚Ä®
- 20% of the primary sales will go directly to the Processing Foundation, 

- Remaining 80% will be donated to a group of individuals that raise money to buy computers for less fortunate architecture students in a university in the eastern part of Turkey. Please read the next paragraph for a detailed explanation

- I will decide what to do with the secondary sales later if there will be any.

About the majority (80%) of the donation : I decided that the donations should be done in a double-blind way, the donator does not know who they are donating to, and the receivers of the donation will not know from whom the donation is coming from, hence I will transfer the funds these individuals mentioned to act as a middle-step. I feel like this is a hard thing to provide a solid proof for, so I recommend if you have doubts and/or straight away do not trust me or this process, do not mint. I will only be able to provide proof of transfer of funds to a third-party. I trust the people I am sending the funds to, we have done this before (not to brag or anything) and I know that we are affecting younger people‚Äôs life in a good way. Also, I believe that the funds raised from this project alone will not be enough to buy one decent config. computer by itself, if it were so, I would have done it differently.‚Ä®‚Ä®About MAGNETIK : ‚Ä®
MAGNETIK plays on the idea of distorting and breaking grids by employing an illusion of fake 3D and tries to make the resulting composition look good with rhythm and color harmony.
 
- 21 palettes,
- 2 background modes : lights on / lights off,
- 3 grid types,
- plus some surprise features‚Ä¶

I encourage you to try and see the variations before minting :)‚Ä®‚Ä®2 of the grid types are based on https://gorillasun.de/blog/an-algorithm-for-irregular-grids by Ahmad Moussa ( https://twitter.com/gorillasu ) and used with his knowledge and kind permission.

gradient formulas are based on https://twitter.com/takawo/status/1505876107492720651?s=20&t=S9aU_oNYyjBieBcEmvUV-g
by Takawo Shunsuke ( https://twitter.com/takawo ) and used with his knowledge and kind permission.

Thank you all in advance and have a good day!

DISCLAIMER : I am not a good coder, I have tried to fix my past mistakes from my earlier projects to make some room for new mistakes :) I am hoping that there isn‚Äôt any huge bugs or anything left so you can enjoy your mint! Please hit me up if you have any concerns after minting and we can discuss a solution.

metadata.name: Modern Times #238
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #312
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Cactigen #8
metadata.description:
This project is the result of a difficult spiritual period in which I learned that art is healing. We all had difficult days, and some of us have turned to art in those days, the art that brought us back to life.
In this project, I have tried to create something of life in the form of fantasy. The connection of form and content, color and shadow, light and dark are all to show our different moods in life and how everything is connected.
Two types of cactus with different shapes, different hours of the day and night, colors are hand-picked and everything you see is completely generative.
I hope you like this project too.
In memory of my wife who loved cacti‚Äôs so much.

metadata.name: Decadence #254
metadata.description:
Decadence should not be misunderstood. Over time, the word has had various meanings (political and cultural) but has also been associated with Symbolism and Aestheticism.

The contemporary definition of decadence emerged in the late 19th century and praised artifice over nature, sophistication over simplicity, at the same time defying contemporary discourse of decline by embracing subjects and styles that critics considered over-refined. 

Nowadays, decadence also refers to stagnation and intellectual exhaustion at a high level of material prosperity and technological development which leads to an excessive indulgence in pleasure or luxury.

In this context, Decadence is a reflection on the collaboration between Jerome Herr and David Mrugala (thedotisblack). A collaboration that started several months ago with a simple grid of random values, that soon became an experiment of creativity, always in the search of expectations, interest in excessive indulgence of visual pleasure, a fascination with the bizarre, all packaged in a series of generative images with an aesthetics that values excess ‚Äì That is Decadence.

- press 's' to save a standard image
- press 'h' to save a high resolution image

Jerome Herr

Jerome Herr is from Luxembourg. Since 2015 he has created generative art with a passion for design and visual explorations. He is an active member of the creative coding community and a successful NFT artist, both on Teia and Fxhash.

David Mrugala

David is a German architect and intermedia artist, who lives in South Korea. He is the founder of thedotisblack, a platform and an archive for research design on (generative) drawings and animations made with code.

metadata.name: Artificialmente Natural #22
metadata.description:
"Artificialmente Natural" is an abstract, natural collection where lines are utilized to create a pseudo-representation of natural colors and textures.

One of my main inspirations comes from my father, who currently lives in Germany. He is always sending beautiful pictures of nature in every season of the year, but especially his latest pics from spring were truly inspiring and thought-provoking. There are 15 palettes representing each season in different ways, but also, some more surrealistic pallettes could appear. Either way, thank you dad, we may live oceans apart but you're still a huge influence in my life.

metadata.name: Garden of Imagination #13
metadata.description:
The more a garden can sharpen all senses, the better.

The garden is one of the most artistic expressions where the five human senses are explored (sight, smell, sound, taste and touch).
It's very good to be impressed by many different colors and shapes, feel the perfume of flowers, feel the textures of plants, taste the fruits and hear the noise of leaves and birds. The more a garden manages to sharpen all the senses, the better it fulfills its role.
The challenge of this project is to provide as many sensations as possible, some you will get visually and others you will need imagination. Imagination is an essential part of this project. There are different species from different cultures that, after becoming relatives, start to interact with each other.

The Garden of Imagination is layered artwork generated from a pool of previously rendered digital assets developed for several months.

- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Swatches #130
metadata.description:
Swatches is the first generative token project by Paul Drzal.

Like photography gels scattered on the light table, the layers combine to create the composition.  A random four-color palette in varying opacities creates your swatch, hand pulled on the screen.

Colors are inspired by the bold stylized drawings of architects Wes Jones and Neil Denari.

metadata.name: CHX-1 #89
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it‚Äôs 1999.

Inspired by 90‚Äôs digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them ‚Äìindividually and as a group‚Äì with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN ‚Äì> p5js ‚Äì> Blockchain
